  "original_title": "\u0db6\u0dd6\u0dc3\u0dca\u0da7\u0dbb\u0dca \u0d91\u0db1\u0dca\u0db1\u0dad\u0dca \u0d8b\u0db4\u0daf\u0dda\u0dc1\u0db1\u0dba WHO \u0dba\u0dcf\u0dc0\u0dad\u0dca\u0d9a\u0dcf\u0dbd\u0dd3\u0db1 \u0d9a\u0dbb\u0dba\u0dd2",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "WHO updates booster vaccination advisory",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "The WHO's Strategic Advisory Group on Immunization (SAGE) has issued a new recommendation on Covid-19 booster vaccines.",
        "They say that the initial vaccine or a double dose of the vaccine followed by a second booster dose should only be given to specific groups of people.",
        "Speaking at a virtual WHO press conference on the issue of vaccines, SAGE president Alejandro Cravioto said the organization's recommendation is not a general recommendation to vaccinate all adults after the first booster.",
        "Counseling is only for the \"highest risk\" population, Cravioto explained. The WHO has already recommended that all adults receive the Covid-19 vaccine, most of which consists of two doses. And follow-up first booster shots four to six months later were recommended.",
        "According to SAGE, the second booster shot should be given first and foremost to the elderly and all immunocompromised people, as well as pregnant women and those with conditions such as diabetes, high blood pressure, and heart, lung, and kidney disease.",
        "\"The recommendation aims to control epidemics and deaths among high-risk populations, but does not issue a general recommendation to vaccinate the entire population after the first booster administration as described in the roadmap,\" Cravioto explained.",
        "Experts at SAGE noted that the current booster recommendations are only for existing vaccines, which are designed to suppress early Covid-19 strains.",
        "The advisory group said it did not know how the coronavirus might evolve in the near future or what characteristics future strains might acquire."
      ],
